Muto's retirement particularly hurts for me because I think his unique brand of genius is really lacking in today's wrestlers.

He wasn't the greatest in-ring performer of all time. He could be sloppy. But he was like a font of creativity or something, and had dynamic movement patterns that were unique and really stood out.
My favorite things about Muto are those little jitters he does when he does the space rolling elbow or a shining wizard, or even that basement dropkick. There's just something about the way he moves that is different and stands out. Muto does so many cool little details that really puts him over as a character, both as himself and as Muta.
I wonder why more wrestlers don't try to find unique mannerisms. I can't really think of anyone else that really understands that in wrestling these days other than Nakamura, and he didn't really get it until late in his career either.

>>8753238
The UUG(p) stuff makes sense since the deal is that TJPW gets to use their name so they want a cut of the merch sales. There is also the fact that CyberAgent can see sales metrics from PWT and 3rd party resellers like White Rabbit and simply decided that it wasn't worth the effort to build and maintain an international store. Just because WU had an upswing in subs from international fans doesn't mean that translates to international merch sales.

Furthermore there are probably big differences in the way the contracts are structured regarding merch cuts for the talent between the different promotions. Maki Itoh sells her merch on PWT independently from TJPW which may have been the result of her contract allowing for one merch internationally while controlling local merch sales and taking a cut. Marufuji, for example has had a long standing Yahoo shop where he sells his curry independently from Noah/Cyberfight despite also including trading cards depicting himself performing moves on other wrestlers from Noah.

tl;dr is that there are probably a number of factors preventing it from happening and we really wouldn't be able to know unless workers from the three promotions started leaking their contract details.

So if you want merch you are going to have to go through a reseller. If you have been a fan of puro for any period of time this shouldn't be that big of a deal as even NJPW fans had to do that before the Tokon global shop opened, and still have to do it in order to purchase exclusive items from the Japan shop.

p.s. Marufuji's curry is pretty good, it ships internationally, and it is definitely spicier than most Japanese style curries.

We have all heard of TJPW prospects bolting for Stardom in search of greater success: Mina Shirakawa and Unagi Sayaka have been Artist and Future champions; Poi has been Artist and High-Speed champion; and Mirai has won the Cinderella.

But what if I tell you that there is one particular member of the Stardom roster who will benefit the most from going the other way around?

That would be Waka Tsukiyama, the promotion's resident punching bag.

Ever since she began wrestling in September 2020, Waka has won exactly one match: a tag match in January 2021. In Stardom? Her best result has been a draw. Every other time, she gets pinned or submitted.

Now some will say, "Be patient! She will eventually get a push! See Lady C." But the way I see it, I think she does not mesh well in Stardom's mostly grim and foreboding atmosphere. Lady C is tall, which is rare among joshi, and that explains why she received a mini-push last year. What does Waka have, besides being born in America and knowing how to speak English (which Mina Shirakawa can also do, but better)?

TJPW, on the other hand, presents a much more relaxed and colorful environment that would fit Waka perfectly. You do not need to be the best wrestler in the world to connect with the fans (though it certainly helps); you just have to be fun to watch and engage with. And it shows in the characters. Miyu Yamashita is the no-nonsense Stardom-style martial artist; Yuka Sakazaki is a majo; Maki Itoh is a vulgar ex-idol; Suzume is a wrestling bee; Shoko Nakajima is a wolf warrior, Miu Watanabe is a boisterous big girl, and so forth.

All of them captivate the audience in one way or another. Waka already has the look, so if she can find her inner voice and turn it into a captivating character, she will garner more success in TJPW than she has ever had in Stardom.
